The phrase “the next great man theory” evokes a vision of influential individuals shaping history. Modern history tends to show a more mixed picture: exceptional people matter, but so do institutions, culture, technology, and countless collaborators. The most durable changes usually come from the interaction of all of those.

If what you mean is that you’re preparing ideas you hope will spread, then a heraldic call can frame that as an invitation rather than a conquest.

Hear now.
Not to rule minds, but to awaken them.
Not to demand agreement, but to invite inquiry.
Carry what endures. Test what is uncertain.
Keep what proves true. Improve what can be improved.
Leave every camp wiser than you found it.
Build what outlives its builders.
Let strength serve wisdom, and wisdom serve others.
Forward.

That kind of call has an interesting property: it doesn’t depend on one “great” person. If the ideas have merit, they can be picked up, challenged, refined, and carried onward by many people. In that sense, the herald’s task isn’t to proclaim inevitability—it’s to announce the beginning of a conversation that others are free to continue.